Data

Skill rating percentile

A total of 205 competiotrs out of 299 had a non-null skill rating. This is an integer that reflects the relative ability of a coder, as it was assessed by its past performance in previous contests. As the absolute values of the skill rating are skewed and it can be hard to interpret them (i.e, having twice as high rating does not mean that a coder is twice as able than another), we used the skill-rating percentile: \[ skill\_pc = 100 \frac{rank(rating) - 1}{\# ratings - 1}. \] The competitors with no rating were ranked last and their skill-rating percentile was computed by breaking ties at random.

Imputation

We matched the registration data with the responses obtained via the registration survey.

About 9% of data obtained from the registration survey were missing; these include key demographics such as education xx% missing; age xx% missing; and gender xx%; as well as self-reported info about time availability. For all these variables, we imputed the missing values at random (see below).

random.imp <- function(x) {
  miss <- is.na(x)
  x.rand <- sample(x[!miss], replace = T)
  ifelse(is.na(x), x.rand, x)
}
races_df$educ <- factor(random.imp(races_df$educ), labels = levels(races_df$educ))
races_df$age <- factor(random.imp(races_df$age), labels = levels(races_df$age))
races_df$male <- random.imp(races_df$male)
races_df$risk <- random.imp(races_df$risk)
for (v in grep("hours", names(races_df))) {
  races_df[,v] <- random.imp(races_df[,v])
}

Curation

To make regression less sensitive to outliers we topcoded the self-reported available time for the contest (aval_time) to 8 hours per day (a few reported they had 24 hours available per day, which seemed unrealistic).

races_df$aval_time <- with(races_df, hours1 + hours2 + hours3 + hours4)
races_df$aval_time_tc <- topcode(races_df$aval_time, 80)

Regressions

Estimate prob. of entry by treatment

lm.entry <- glm(100 * (nsub > 0) ~ treatment + large + center(skill_pc), data = races_df)
lm.entry1 <- update(lm.entry, ~ . + center(aval_time_tc/8) + region)
lm.entry2 <- update(lm.entry1, ~ . + I(create_year > 2010))
lm.entry3 <- update(lm.entry1, ~ . + educ)
lm.entry4 <- update(lm.entry1, ~ . + age)
lm.entry5 <- update(lm.entry1, ~ . + male)
lm.entry6 <- update(lm.entry1, ~ . + risk)
ols.entry <- lapply(objects(pattern = "lm.entry"), get)
ols.entry.interact <- lapply(ols.entry, update, formula = ~ . + treatment:large)
ols.entry.skill.interact <- lapply(ols.entry, update, formula = ~ . + treatment:center(skill_pc))
ols.entry.time.interact <- lapply(ols.entry, update, formula = ~ . + treatment:center(aval_time_tc/8))
binom.entry <- lapply(ols.entry, update, formula = nsub > 0 ~ ., family = "binomial")
binom.entry.interact <- lapply(ols.entry.interact, update, formula = nsub > 0 ~ ., family = "binomial")

Appendix

Diagnostic plots for logistic models

par(mfrow = c(3,3))
mod <- binom.entry
for (i in 1:length(mod)) {
  pred <- predict(mod[[i]])
  res <- resid(mod[[i]])
  arm::binnedplot(pred, res, nclass = 15)
}
